        <Document ID="56">
            <Title>Cornerstone</Title>
            <Text>The account of God’s interactions with Abram begins with a call for Abram to leave his ancestral people and homeland: ‘Now the LORD said to Abram, “Go from your country and your kindred and your father’s house to the land that I will show you”’(Gen. 12:1, ESV). Leaving the comfort of home, family, and familiar surroundings can be quite a challenge because such a transition can remove one from the love, care, acceptance, and security of a strong support system - especially in ancient nomadic cultures. 
However, this is exactly what God demanded of Abram. The word “go” is lek-leka in Hebrew, which expresses that Abram is to “determinately dissociate himself” from his current environment (Bruce Waltke, Genesis: A commentary, 205). Hebrews 11:8 makes it clear that Abram forsook his home in obedience to God’s call. He obeyed not even knowing where he was going! He exchanged the known for the unknown, the familiar for the unfamiliar. God called Abram to a new life, but he had to leave his old life behind. Likewise, Christians have been called to a new life of discipleship which involves separation from the past life of sin, separation from the world, and possibly separation from family and friends.


</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="57">
            <Title>Inscription</Title>
            <Text>Abram looms over Biblical history as the father of the faithful. His journey to this status began at age 75 when God called him leave his people and homeland. Abram willingly left Haran with his wife Sarai, his nephew Lot, along with their belongings and people they acquired. In doing so, Abram demonstrated a high level of commitment to God and His promises. He demonstrated the ability to listen to God and the faith to allow God to work out the details of His plan.</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="58">
            <Title>Cornerstone</Title>
            <Text>God’s promises to Abraham begins with the promise of land (12:1). When Abraham left Haran with Sarai, Lot and all of their possessions, they set out for the land of Canaan (12:5). When they arrived, they discovered that the territory was already inhabited by Canaanites. When Abraham arrived at Shechem the Lord appeared and reassured him - “to your offspring I will give this land” (12:7). The promised land definitely refers to Canaan, also known as Palestine, the land of Israel. In response to God’s reassurance Abraham built an altar and worshiped God. Even though people already inhabited the land, Abraham demonstrated that faith in God’s promise displays itself through actions. He reminds us that faith begins with hearing God’s word and grows as we continue to obey God’s word. A living faith leads to a life of devotion to and worship of God.
As Abraham continued to explore the land and build altars to God, we know that he was also looking forward to an eternal land, for the Scripture says “he was looking forward to the city that has foundations, whose designer and builder is God”. God’s promise to Abraham included the assurance of an eternal city and homeland that transcended Canaan. He journeyed as a foreigner looking forward to the fulfillment of the same promise given to us as Christians - the promise of a new heavens and a new earth (2 Peter 3:13). We will inherit the promise of a renewed universe if we, like Abraham, respond to God in faithful obedience (Romans 4:13). Thus, the promised land not only refers to Canaan but it also is a symbol of the holy city, the New Jerusalem, that will come down out of heaven from God (Revelation 21:2).
Just imagine how the fulfillment of the promised land  would affect Abraham’s life. It would mean removal of the obstacles currently in place in Canaan. He would be able to settle down. He could avoid being exposed to different kinds of dangers, threats and attacks upon his family. In a sense, the fulfillment of the promise would bring victory and rest to Abraham., but it was not fulfilled during his lifetime. In the meantime, Abraham would have to continue to press onward trusting God’s word, guidance, and protection. As Christians, we are commanded to “strive to enter that rest, so that no one may fall by the same sort of disobedience. For the word of God is living and active, sharper than any two-edged sword, piercing to the division of soul and of spirit, of joints and of marrow, and discerning the thoughts and intentions of the heart. And no creature is hidden from his sight, but all are naked and exposed to the eyes of him to whom we must give account” (Hebrews 4:11-13).
God also promised to make Abraham’s name great (12:2). Waltke writes “in the ancient Near East, a name was not merely a label but a revelation of character. Thus a great name entails not only fame but high social esteem as a man of superior character” (A Commentary on Genesis, p. 205). God indeed did make Abraham’s name known: Melchizedek, the high priest of God at Salem recognized him as blessed by God (14); the rulers of his day recognized Abraham as a mighty prince (21:22-34; 23:6); and he was known as a prophet (20:7). Furthermore, Abraham’s name is great throughout history as the ancestral father of Jewish and Arab peoples. More importantly, the name of Abraham is synonymous with faith.  
In addition, God promised to bless and make Abraham great so that he would be a blessing to others. In other words, God promised to use Abraham to have positive impact on the world around him and beyond (12:3). As a result of his response to God’s call, Abraham blessed generations of saints with a great example of faith. The NT writers exalt Abraham as the supreme example of what it means to have a faith that God honors (Romans 4; Galatians 3; Hebrews 11:3-10; James 2:18-23). What made Abraham’s faith so great? Was it because he lived a sinless life? No. In fact, Abraham was plagued by many of the same weaknesses and sins as we are. However, Abraham believed God against the odds. He left Haran for the promised land despite not having the details of the plan or of the final destination. He continued to trust God to fulfill his God despite never possessing the land. He believed that he would become the ancestral father of a great nation despite years of unsuccessful attempts to bear children through Sarai. He believed that God would use him to bless the world through the promised Seed - the Savior -  despite his past life of idolatry and paganism.
Thus the greatest blessing to come through Abraham would be Jesus, the promised Seed through whom salvation would be available to all the world. Galatians 3:8-9 says, “And the Scripture, foreseeing that God would justify the Gentiles by faith, preached the Gospel beforehand to Abraham, saying, ‘In you shall all the nations be blessed.’ So then, those who are of faith are blessed along with Abraham, the man of faith.” This is the climax of God’s promises to Abraham. God’s plan of redemption begins with Abraham in Canaan. The promised seed will come through the great nation of Abraham’s loins, Israel. This promised seed, Jesus, is God’s one and only Son who gave His life to atone for the sins of the entire world (1 John 2:2). 
However, Jesus triumphed over the grave and after his resurrection He commissioned his followers to “Go therefore and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit, teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you. And behold, I am with you always, to the end of the age” (Matthew 28:19-20). Just as God called Abraham, we have been called by God through the gospel to follow Jesus, the promised Seed. Those who respond to the gospel are heirs to the promises God made to Abraham. In turn, we are to extend this blessings to others through the teaching and preaching of the gospel. </Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="59">
            <Title>Inscription</Title>
            <Text>God’s call to leave his country and his family was paired with great promises. What made Abraham’s faith response so remarkable was that his life circumstances would have led most people to reject God’s call. Furthermore, many of the promises were never fully realized during his lifetime. Just as God called Abraham to a difficult journey with great blessings, Jesus calls His people to a similar journey through the Sermon on the Mount. In this sermon, the Lord offer several blessings to potential followers. These blessings include the following:

“Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven. 
“Blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth. 
“Blessed are those who are persecuted for righteousness’ sake, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven. (Matthew 5:3,5,10)

The Lord’s call to discipleship through the Gospel is a difficult journey for us. The character virtues of humility, meekness, submission to persecution for the sake of righteousness does not appeal to us. However, the promises of finding life in God’s kingdom and inheriting life on the new heavens and earth can only be realized by embarking on this journey. We can experience the blessings offered by Jesus because one man, Abraham, decided to faithfully respond to God’s call thousands of years ago. We have been entrusted with the Gospel message to call all people to follow Christ. This is how we participate in God’s great promise to Abraham that in him all the world will be blessed. As we do so, we have the promise of Christ presence to the end of the age and we can be assured that God will be faithful to His promises.</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="60">
            <Title>Foundation</Title>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="61">
            <Title>Cornerstone</Title>
            <Text>“Now there was a famine in the land. So Abram went down to Egypt to sojourn there, for the famine was severe in the land” (12:10). After having obeyed God’s call to go to Canaan and receiving reassurance of the promise, Abraham is confronted with a difficult trial of his faith - he finds himself in the midst of a severe famine. The future looks dim in Canaan. This situation presented an issue of life and death to Abraham and his family. He may have asked God at this point, “I thought you were going to make me into a great nation?” Abraham now had to choose between remaining in the land of promise, thus risking starvation or moving on to greener pastures where his family could survive. In Abraham’s day Egypt was a popular destination to escape famine because agriculture in Egypt was more dependent on the regular flooding of the Nile river. So, Abraham decided to take matters into his own hands and moved his family to Egypt. Did his decision represent a lack of faith in God’s ability to fulfill His promises in Canaan? Maybe so. On the other hand, Abraham may have rationalized that a dead man could not father a great nation.
“When he was about to enter Egypt, he said to Sarai his wife, ‘I know that you are a woman beautiful in appearance, and when the Egyptians see you, they will say, ‘This is his wife.’ Then they will kill me, but they will let you live. Say you are my sister, that it may go well with me because of you, and that my life may be spared for your sake’” (12:11-13). There is no doubt that now Abraham demonstrates a lack of faith driven by fear and self-preservation. Instead of trusting God to protect him, Abraham made a self-centered decision to engage in deception. We learn from Genesis 20:13 that when God called him to leave his father’s house, Abraham feared losing his life to powerful men in dangerous territories who might be attracted to his beautiful wife. Now that they are about to enter Egypt and face Pharaoh, Abraham convinces Sarah to enact their brother-sister narrative so that he might receive a bride price from interested suitors. 
Does this sound like the same man who demonstrated great faith by leaving family, friends, and homeland in pursuit of a promise he has not seen? Is this the same man who displayed great devotion to God by building altars of worship to the one true God in pagan lands? Here we see that Abraham, known as the friend of God and father of the faithful, struggled with sin and fear as we do today. The Scriptures provide plenty examples of God’s faithful succumbing to sin: Noah and his drunkenness; David and Bathsheba; and Peter’s denial of the Lord. Abraham’s actions shows how deceitful sin is and that we all need to be watchful and vigilant in prayer because the flesh will never be completely  done away with in this life. We all should keep in mind the admonition “therefore let anyone who thinks that he stands take heed lest he fall” (1 Corinthians 10:12).
“When Abram entered Egypt, the Egyptians saw that the woman was very beautiful. And when the princes of Pharaoh saw her, they praised her to Pharaoh. And the woman was taken into Pharaoh’s house. And for her sake he dealt well with Abram; and he had sheep, oxen, male donkeys, male servants, female servants, female donkeys, and camels” (12:14-16). Abraham’s fears become realized. Sarah’s beauty has captured the attention of Pharaoh’s princes and consequently she ends up in Pharaoh’s house! In exchange, Abraham is living the high life as he receives animals and servants. What might Sarah be thinking and feeling at this point? Anger? Abandonment? Disappointment? We don’t know Sarah’s state of mind at this point but Abraham’s decision jeopardized her, their marriage, and the fulfillment of God’s promises in their lives. His actions reminds us that we often allow circumstances rather than God’s word to drive our behavior. Just as Abraham, we make decisions which negatively impact our loved ones and distract us from pursuing God’s will. However, as the narrative proceeds, we discover that by God’s grace and mercy we can get back on track. God is willing and able to guide us back to pursuing His will. 
“But the Lord afflicted Pharaoh and his house with great plagues because of Sarai, Abram’s wife. So Pharaoh called Abram and said, ‘What is this you have done to me? Why did you not tell me that she was your wife? Why did you say, ‘She is my sister,’ so that I took her for my wife? Now then, here is your wife; take her, and go.’ And Pharaoh gave men orders concerning him, and they sent him away with his wife and all that he had” (12:17-20). Abraham had gotten himself and Sarah into a mess, but God did not give up on him. God did not say, “Abraham, since you made such a foolish, fearful decision you’re disqualified from inheriting my promises. I’m going to call someone else to do what you couldn’t!” Instead, God made it known to Pharaoh  that Sarah was another man’s wife! God delivered Sarah from what appeared to be a hopeless situation. God remained faithful to His promises even though Abraham was temporarily unfaithful. What a great God we serve! This episode bears witness to the truth that God “does not deal with us according to our sins, nor repay us according to our iniquities” (Psalm 103:10). Though Abraham was a great man of faith, he did not merit the promises of God.
After Pharaoh became aware of Sarah’s marital status, he returned her to Abraham and sent them away from Egypt with more possessions than they arrived with. One of those possessions made have included Hagar, Sarah’s personal maid servant. If so, we see that though God shows us mercy and grace through our sins and failures, our choices have enduring consequences. As we live with the ongoing effects of our sinful choices we often struggle with  self-condemnation. However, as with Abraham, we must remind ourselves that God is committed to completing His work of transformation within us until the return of Jesus Christ (Philippians 1:6). 
Furthermore, God can use our failures and sins to teach us valuable lessons in order to prevent us from making more tragic decisions in the future. We learn from this episode that the flesh is at war against the Spirit within us and if we let down our guard the old nature will overpower  our best intentions. Satan, the enemy of our souls, seeks our ultimate destruction; therefore, we ought to be vigilant every moment of our lives. The apostle Peter puts it this way: “Humble yourselves, therefore, under the mighty hand of God so That at the proper time he may exalt you, casting all your anxieties on him, because he cares for you. Be sober-minded, be watchful. Your adversary the devil prowls around like a roaring lion, seeking someone to devour” (1 Peter 5:6-8).
</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="62">
            <Title>Inscription</Title>
            <Text>Though Abraham was a man of great faith, we read that he had ‘feet of clay’ just as we do. When confronted with a dire situation and an encounter with the powerful Egyptians, Abraham resorted to deception because he doubted God’s willingness and ability to deliver him. Abraham focused on the circumstances and allowed fear to drive his decisions rather than faith. This reminds us of the apostle Peter’s experience of walking on water. When he began to focus on the windstorm rather than Jesus, he became afraid and began to sink. The Lord gracefully delivered Peter from drowning just as God delivered Sarah from the clutches of Pharaoh. God provides the same grace to His children today.
The antidote to fear of man and situations is focus on the power and goodness of the Lord. The apostle Paul wrote, “and we know that for those who love God all things work together for good, for those who are called according to his purpose” (Romans 8:28). We serve a God who uses the good and bad to accomplish His plans for His people. No matter how dire the situation, how the big the obstacles, or how overwhelming the odds may seem God will protect and guide His people by His providential power.</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="63">
            <Title>Foundation</Title>
            <Text>“So Abram went up from Egypt, he and his wife and all that he had, and Lot with him, into the Negeb.” After a temporary lapse of faith in Egypt on Abraham’s part, God delivered Sarah from the hands of the Egyptians. Abraham traveled south through the Negeb back to the area between Bethel and Ai, the place he originally settled after leaving Haran. God has blessed Abraham through his recent episode - he is now “very rich in livestock, in silver, and in gold”, indicating that Abraham left Egypt more wealthy than when he arrived. However, riches (nor failure) did not cause him to forget God for the passage reads “and there Abram called upon the name of the Lord” (13:4). Abraham had repented of the sin he had committed in Egypt and consequently, God had forgiven and blessed him. As Christians, when we turn from our sins and sincerely call upon the Lord to forgive us, we experience restoration of sweet fellowship with God. In addition, God can use us in greater service than before. As we will discover in the case of Abraham relationship with his nephew Lot, such blessings do not eliminate trials from our lives. </Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="64">
            <Title>Cornerstone</Title>
            <Text>“And Lot, who went with Abram, also had flocks and herds and tents” (13:5). Lot was the son of Abraham’s brother, Haran. Obviously the two shared a close bond, for Abraham took Lot under his wings after the death of Haran. He accompanied Abraham when God called him to leave his homeland. As a result of his association with Abraham, Lot prospered and grew wealthy to the point that the land they lived in could not support both their livestock (13:6). Oftentimes we think that more money and wealth will eliminate the problems of our lives, but here we see the opposite - it created more problems and tension! Verse 7 says “and there was strife between the herdsmen of Abram’s livestock and the herdsmen of Lot’s livestock. At that time the Canaanites and the Perizzites were dwelling in the land.” Increased blessings led to disputing between the herdsmen of Abraham and Lot due to the lack of land resources. This trial presented another test of Abraham’s faith. How will he deal with the conflict amongst his own family caravan? Will he be passive and allow it to boil to the point of severe conflict? Whatever course of action he would decide upon, the native peoples of the land (the Canaanites and Perizzites) would be witnessing the outcome of the situation. Whenever conflicts arise among Christians, we should view such trials as opportunities to bear strong witness for God to a watching world. 
Notice Abraham’s loving response - “Then Abram said to Lot, “Let there be no strife between you and me, and between your herdsmen and my herdsmen, for we are kinsmen” (13:8). Abraham demonstrates love for Lot by expressing his desire to keep peace between their workers. He doesn’t want the conflict to escalate to the point of more strife because he values Lot’s relationship. It should be remembered that Abraham and Sarah have not conceived children, so most likely he views and loves Lot as a son. Furthermore, Lot had demonstrated great loyalty  in joining Abraham as he followed God and sought the promised land. They would have needed to stick together as they faced great dangers and enemies. Therefore, Abraham sought peace to maintain a good relationship with Lot. Whenever we experience conflicts in our relationships, whether they be in the home, church or at work, we should remember the admonition of Paul to “pursue what makes for peace and for mutual up-building” (Romans 14:19).
What made Abraham’s response even more remarkable is that he gave Lot the option to choose whatever area he wanted to settle (13:9)! Instead of fighting for his rights to the land because he was the head of the family, the leader, and the person to whom God had promised the land, Abraham demonstrated great humility, generosity and faith in giving up his claim to choose first! Abraham shows what is means to “do nothing from selfish ambition or conceit, but in humility count others more significant than yourselves” (Php. 2:3). As Christians, we are to relinquish our rights to choose first in order to enrich others. Abraham was able to do this because he firmly believed God’s promise to ultimately give him the land. When we are focused on God promises and secured in Christ, we become less concerned about accumulating money and possessions. When we are willing to seek God and His righteousness above all else, we are able live selflessly because we know that God will meet all of our needs. 
Did Lot return the favor by declining first choice to the land? No. In contrast to Abraham, he jumped at the opportunity to enrich himself: “And Lot lifted up his eyes and saw that the Jordan Valley was well watered everywhere like the garden of the Lord, like the land of Egypt, in the direction of Zoar” (13:10a). Just as Eve was attracted by the fruit of the forbidden tree (Genesis 3:6), Lot is attracted what he sees in the Jordan Valley where the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah were located. Instead of trusting God and walking by faith, Lot chooses to walk by selfishness and greed. Even though Abraham had demonstrated great love for Lot by rearing him, educating him and contributing blessings to him, Lot chose what he thought was the best thing for himself. Sooner and later, Lot’s choices will prove to be unwise and disastrous for him and all those with him. When we are misled by the lust of the flesh, the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life (as Lot was), we make similar decisions filled with negative spiritual impact. Therefore, we must make decisions such as where to live and work, who to date and marry, and what to entertain ourselves with in light of God’s will. That’s why it is important to “not be conformed to this world, but be transformed by the renewal of your mind, that by testing you may discern what is the will of God, what is good and acceptable and perfect” (Romans 12:2).
After Lot separated from him and settled near the wicked men of Sodom, God reaffirmed his promises to Abraham. Lot had selfishly lifted up his eyes and choose land that seemed best for himself settle, but God instructed Abraham, “lift up your eyes and look from the place where you are, northward and southward and eastward and westward, for all the land that you see I will give to you and to your offspring forever” (13:14-15). What irony! In a situation in which Abraham seemed to have gotten a raw deal, God lets him know that this is only a temporary setback! God’s sovereign will is to give the entire land (including what Lot chose for himself) to Abraham and his descendants to possess forever. Through this entire ordeal, Abraham lifted up his eyes in humility and selflessness. Through this entire trial, Abraham lifted up his eyes to God in faith and trust. And now God has reaffirmed his covenant with Abraham, letting him know that the current state of affairs will not last forever. 
Abraham’s exemplary faith in this situation reminds us of the Beatitude, “blessed are the meek, for they shall inherit the earth” (Matt. 5:5). Meekness should not be equated with weakness. We should remember that Abraham was by no means inferior to Lot, for he was a highly skilled military leader who could have easily dominated the situation. By example, he teaches us to be humble, dependent on God, and willing to look not only to our own interests, but also to the interests of others (Php. 2:4). Our Lord Jesus put forth the supreme example of selflessness who “though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich” (2 Corinthians 8:9)
Abraham also teaches us that the proper response to God’s grace is a life of worship. After the Lord reaffirmed his promises, “Abram moved his tent and came and settled by the oaks of Mamre, which are at Hebron, and there he built an altar to the Lord” (12:18). As Abraham continued on his journey of faith in Canaan, he worshiped and left witness that the true and living God had promised him the land. On our journey of faith, we are to present ourselves as living sacrifices holy and acceptable to God, which is our spiritual worship (Romans 12:1). In doing so, we bear witness to the mercies of God.

</Text>
