        <Document ID="67">
            <Title>Cornerstone</Title>
            <Text>“Then one who had escaped came and told Abram the Hebrew, who was living by the oaks of Mamre the Amorite, brother of Eshcol and of Aner. These were allies of Abram” (14:13). Here, Abraham is known as ‘the Hebrew’, an ethnic term connected with Eber (Waltke, p.231). Eber was the last ancestor in the genealogy of Shem before God disrupted the building of the tower of Babel (10:21-25). Abraham is a legitimate descendant of Shem, which distinguishes him from the other residents of Canaan. 
Abraham had formed an alliance with Mamre the Amorite and his two brothers prior to the defeat of Sodom and the capture of Lot. Apparently, Abraham wisely anticipated the need to ally himself with reliable men who would join him to combat unseen dangers and opposition. He bore witness to the truth of the proverb that says “ And though a man might prevail against one who is alone, two will withstand him — a threefold cord is not quickly broken” (Ecclesiastes 4:12). We should follow Abraham’s example by forming strong relationships with other Christians within the local congregation so that we can have strong spiritual support when facing struggles and opposition. In doing so we fulfill the command to “bear one another’s burdens, and so fulfill the law of Christ” (Galatians 6:2). Our faith journey is filled with burdens which God does not intend for us to carry alone. Therefore, it is important that we form relationships with other Christians in which we support one another. 
“When Abram heard that his kinsman had been taken captive, he led forth his trained men, born in his house, 318 of them, and went in pursuit as far as Dan” (14:14). After receiving the report, he organizes a military mission with 318 of his most trusted, trained men to rescue Lot from captivity. In contrast to his actions in Egypt where he allowed fear to rule him, here Abraham displays great courage and faith.  When faced with opposition to our faith or with challenging situations that threaten in some way, we’re often tempted to give in to fear. However, just as Abraham trusted that God’s promises to make him a great nation would guarantee military victory, we must trust that God’s promises to protect us guarantees our ultimate victory over all opposition. One such promise can be found in Hebrews 13:5b-6: “for he has said, ‘I will never leave you nor forsake you.’ So we can confidently say, ‘The Lord is my helper; I will not fear; what can man do to me?’”. 
Abraham’s mission to rescue Lot ended with the defeat of the enemies. Verse 16 says, “then he brought back all the possessions, and also brought back his kinsman Lot with his possessions, and the women and the people.” Despite the formidable opposition he faced, Abraham had successfully organized and executed a mission to save Lot and the people with him. We should note that Abraham could have made several excuses not to save Lot: 1) Lot had acted selfishly in taking the best land for himself; 2) Lot was worldly and deserving of the circumstances he fell into or 3) Lot’s captors were strong and formidable. Instead, Abraham refused to let Lot remain enslaved to his captors. Oftentimes we adopt a negative attitude towards our fellow Christians who ‘mess up’ their lives through poor decisions. We must remember that Scripture teaches us that whenever a fellow Christian “is caught in any transgression, you who are spiritual should restore him in a spirit of gentleness” (Galatians 6:1). Whenever we see a fellow Christian enslaved or ensnared in sin, we are to act with courage and love to do all we can to free them. This requires the humility to recognize that we all are susceptible to sins such as immorality, drunkenness, drugs, gluttony, lust, worldly ambition, etc. Keeping in mind that Christ died for us while we were sinners (and his enemies!) should help us to adopt the proper attitude we need in such situations. 
Through this event, God is fulfilling His promise to make Abraham’s name great (Genesis 12:2). Melchizedek, the king of Salem and priest of God, recognized this and hosted a royal banquet declaring Abraham as blessed and protected by “God Most High, Possessor of heaven and earth” (Genesis 14:19-20a). In the presence of thousands of Canaanites who had just been freed, Melchizedek praised God as the One behind Abraham’s success! By God’s power, Abraham had just brought stability and peace to the land of Canaan, thus being an instrument of God’s blessing to others. So, this occasion served as an excellent opportunity to bear witness to the one true God! In Matthew 5:16 Jesus commanded “In the same way, let your light shine before others, so that they may see your good works and give glory to your Father who is in heaven.” As we live out our faith other people will notice. When that happens, we should use such opportunities to direct their attention to God.
In response to Melchizedek’s recognition, Abraham gave him a tenth of the possessions he gained in the victory (Genesis 14:20b). This is the first explicit reference in Scripture to what will become known as the ‘tithe’. In giving him a tenth of everthing, Abraham recognized Melchizedek as the legitimate priest and king of his God (Waltke, p. 235). On the other hand, when the king of Sodom approached him with a proposal to share the spoils of war, Abraham responded “I have lifted my hand to the Lord, God Most High, Possessor of heaven and earth, that I would not take a thread or a sandal strap or anything that is yours, lest you should say, ‘I have made Abram rich’” (Genesis 14:22b-23). Evidently, the wicked king had ulterior motives behind his proposal which would had indebted Abraham in the eyes of the Canaanites. Abraham refuses to compromise and gives all the possessions he acquired to his allies Aner, Eshcol, and Mamre. In doing so, Abraham expresses his complete dependence upon God to supply his needs. Let us remember that God richly provides for all of our needs “according to His riches in glory in Christ Jesus” (Philippians 4:19).</Text>
