            <Title>Foundation</Title>
            <Text>In Genesis 14, Abraham demonstrated great faith in God in saving Lot and defeating a powerful Mesopotamian alliance lead by Chedorlaomer. God’s promise to make Abraham’s great is fulfilled at the great banquet hosted by God’s high priest, Melchizedek. Refusing to compromise with the king of Sodom, Abraham demonstrated appreciation to his own alliance by giving them the spoils of the victory. Things seem to be looking up for Abraham.
However, Abraham (and Sarah) have yet to give birth to a biological son through whom he would become a great nation. Years had passed since the initial call to leave his homeland and now Abraham was beginning to wonder if God intended to bless him with a son through Sarah. Like Abraham, we often experience a certain level of doubt when circumstances and events call into question God’s goodness or love. Oftentimes, personal struggles lead to question God’s ability to transform us to be more like Christ. At other times, our emotions seem to be a better indicator of reality rather than the truth of God’s words.  
We will discover in Genesis 15 that God doesn’t abandon us during seasons of doubt. Rather, God provides the assurances we need to continue to walk by faith. </Text>
