2. What had Abram built at this place (v4)? Describe what this is. (Think: Abram built these in many places. What does this tell us about his character?)

Abram built an altar near Bethel
The physical symbol is a reminder to Abraham of God’s promises and Abraham’s earlier faith. The narrator’s comment on this image suggests to the reader that Abraham has returned to a position of faith, the place where the reader should also dwell. Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001).

3. What problem arose between Lot and Abram and what was the cause of the problem?

Disputing arose between the herdsmen of Abram and Lot due to lack of land space

4. What proposal did Abram make to solve the problem? What does this say about Abram’s character?

He gave Lot the option to choose whatever area he wanted to settle
Abram offers Lot a choice between going “right” or “left” when they separate (Gen 13:9). In biblical geography, “right” often indicates the south, so “left” here would indicate the north (see Wenham 1987, 297).
Giving first choice to Lot was both generous and risky. Commentators usually emphasize Abram’s magnanimity, his noble gesture in giving Lot first choice, as a sign of his renewed trust in Yahweh to fulfill the promise

5. List and explain at least three passages elsewhere that show the importance of peace and making peace. (Think: Under what circumstances may we give in to others to have peace, and under what circumstances would it be wrong to do so?)

The commendation of peacemakers
Mt 5:9 Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called sons of God.
Ro 14:19 So then let us pursue what makes for peace and for mutual upbuilding.
The importance of pursuing peace
Ro 12:18 If possible, so far as it depends on you, live peaceably with all.
Heb 12:14 Strive for peace with everyone, and for the holiness without which no one will see the Lord
Sometimes brothers must separate for the sake of peace Waltke, B. K., &amp; Fredricks, C. J. (2001).

6. What choice did Lot make and why?

Lot chose the Jordan Valley, near Sodom
The attraction of the Jordan Valley is made evident in Gen 13:10 where the land is described as “well-watered” like “Egypt” and the “garden of Yahweh.”

7. What were the people like in the area Lot moved to?

The men of Sodom were very wicked
Sodomites, not living in the promised land, are culpable as sinners against Yahweh. Hamilton, V. P. (1990). 

8. Special Assignment: Using cross references, find and explain passages that show what results Lot’s choice eventually brought on him and his family. (Think: What lessons can we learn about the danger of material attractions?)

Lot’s choice to go east represents separation—from Abram, from the promised land, and from God. 
In Genesis, “east” frequently indicates moving in a direction away from God or toward danger (compare the expulsion from Eden in Gen 3:24 or Cain’s exile in Gen 4:16; see Mathews 2005, 130–1; McKeown 2008, 84).
Abram trusts Yahweh for provision, while Lot chooses what appears to be the best land for himself. Like Eve in Gen 3:6, Lot is attracted by the deceptively good appearance of what he sees.
His decision creates a chain of events that will lead to the founding of the Moabites and the Ammonites as distinct peoples in the Transjordan region, outside of Canaan (see Gen 19:30–38).
Lot’s decision making process (allowing himself to be guided by what attracts) will put him in dire circumstances. Lot chooses by sight in contrast to Abram’s faithful choice to trust God. 

