&quot;f. The major battle was fought in the valley of the Salt Sea, that is, the Dead Sea (v. 8).
g. The kings of Sodom and Gomorrah suffered a humiliating defeat (vv. 10–11). The author specifically mentions what happened to these two kings, pointing out an unusual fact. They fled and hid out in the tar pits—bitumen or asphalt pits—while the rest of their army fled into the surrounding mountains (v. 10). The Hebrew word for “they fell” can either mean to perish or to lower and humiliate oneself. The king of Sodom was still alive in verse 17, thus the meaning must be that the two kings were defeated in battle, utterly debased and humiliated. They had to crawl and hide out in the tar pits of the area. The valley of the Salt Sea (Dead Sea) was full of bitumen pits from which tar or asphalt was taken in ancient days.
