            <Title>When a brother is enslaved by some enemy,</Title>
            <Text>When a brother is enslaved by some enemy, believers must arise to help free the brother, no matter how great the opposition. This was exactly what Abram did. But note: Abram could have found many reasons why he should not help Lot.
⇒Lot had done a terrible wrong against Abram: he had acted with greed and selfishly usurped Abram’s rights to the best land for his ranch.
⇒Lot had taken the best land for himself, leaving Abram to fend for himself on the less desirable land. (See outline and notes—Ge. 13:5–18 for more discussion.) Abram could have allowed harsh feelings to develop against Lot for having wronged him.
⇒Lot was worldly, attracted by the bright lights, pleasures, and possessions offered by the ungodly of the cities. Abram could have responded by saying that Lot was getting what he deserved, that God’s judgment was falling upon Lot because of his worldliness.
⇒Lot had been captured by a strong enemy, a large force of invaders. Humanly, it was impossible for Abram to rescue Lot.
