        <Document ID="273">
            <Title>Abraham Seeks Reasurrance</Title>
            <Text>Abraham’s response indicates that the reward God speaks of includes offspring: “O Lord God, what will you give me, for I continue childless, and the heir of my house is Eliezer of Damascus?” (Genesis 15:2). Abraham goes on to express a sense of hopelessness. God’s delay has led Abraham to conclude that it looks like his chief servant, Eliezer, will end up being his heir. Waltke writes that there is “some evidence that in Abraham’s culture a childless man could adopt someone to be the guardian and heir of his estate as compensation for the person’s performing the duties of a son. If a son was subsequently born, the adopted man could not disinherit the natural son” (p. 241). It appears that Abraham has an alternate plan in place should he and Sarah fail to conceive a son. 
However, God reassured Abraham that he and Sarah will give birth to a son who will be his heir. In the midst of Abraham’s concern about not yet having a son, the Lord takes him outside during the night and tells him that he will produce as many offspring as the number of stars in the sky! Abraham’s response reveals the reason why he is called the father of the faithful: “And he believed the Lord, and he counted it to him as righteousness” (Genesis 15:6). Abraham paid more attention to God’s promise than to the fact that he and Sarah seemed to be rapidly passing the age of childbearing. Instead of focusing on Sarah’s barrenness, Abraham trusted God’s ability and willingness to bless them with a son. Paul describes Abraham’s faith as being “fully convinced that God was able to do what he had promised” (Romans 4:21). Because of his faith, God declared Abraham righteous (or justified).
What was true of Abraham is true of us today. All of us have sinned and fallen short of God’s glory. We have created a debt with God that we can never repay. We all stand guilty in God’s courtroom. However, God promises to make us righteous through the work of Jesus Christ (Romans 3:21-25). God calls us to completely trust his promise and to fix our eyes upon Jesus, the author and perfecter of our faith (Hebrews 12:2). Cottrell provides a helpful analogy of justifying faith. It is not easy for a drowning person to relax and let a lifeguard to take control of him in order to pull him to safety. The drowning person will instinctly continue to try to save self, thus hindering the lifeguard’s efforts. In order to be saved, the person must allow the lifeguard to do what he is trained to do. In the same manner, if we want to be made righteous like Abraham, we must give up trying to save ourselves. Instead, we must fully accept and rest in God’s gracious promise of forgiveness through Jesus. The apostle Paul wrote, “So in Christ Jesus you are all children of God through faith, for all of you who were baptized into Christ have clothed yourselves with Christ” (Galatians 3:26-27). It is through faith that we become Abraham’s seed and heir according to the promise God gave to him (Galatians 3:28-29).</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="274">
            <Title>God Makes a Covenant</Title>
            <Text>Abraham believed God’s promise concerning offspring, but he asks for tangible proof that the land will become his (Genesis 15:8). What follows is a covenant ritual ceremony initiated by the Lord, who instructs Abraham to bring him a heifer, a female goat, a ram, a turtledove, and a young pigeon. The ceremony proceeded with Abraham cutting the large animals in half, laying the pieces in opposite rows with the birds at opposite ends. Abraham falls into a divinely induced deep sleep at sunset and for the first time the Lord gives him the specific details of how he will possess the land of Canaan. God reveals to Abraham that himself will not possess it, but that his offspring will come into possession of the land after four hundred years of servitude in another land. Their return to Canaan will be the occasion of God judging the Amorites (representative of the ten nations listed in Genesis 15:19-21). When the Amorite culture becomes totally saturated with sin, God will use Abraham’s offspring to dispossess them of the land.
The ceremony reaches a high point when God appears to Abraham to finalize (cut) the covenant - “When the sun had gone down and it was dark, behold, a smoking fire pot and a flaming torch passed between these pieces” (Genesis 15:17). Fire is often a symbol of the presence of God in Scripture (Exodus 3:1-6; 13:21; 19:16f; Acts 2:1-4). Here, God alone passes through the opposite rows of the sacrificed animals. God alone ratified His covenant with Abraham - this was a one-sided affair. By grace, God ‘obliges’ upon himself “to implement his promise of descendants, and especially of land, to Abram and to his descendants” (Hamilton, p.438). God goes great length to assure Abraham that He will definitely fulfill His promises. Likewise for us, at the cross of Calvary God gave us the greatest evidence of His love for us. With confidence, we can sing:
“To God be the glory, great things He has done, so loved He the 	world that He gave us His Son, who yielded his life our redemption to win, and opened the life-gate that all may go in” (To God Be The Glory, Fanny Crosby, 1872).
</Text>
