            <Title>Genesis 20</Title>
            <Text>Overview
Question: How do you respond to repeated failures, weaknesses and sins?

Gen 20:1–2
Abraham moves to Gerar, in the territory of the Negeb between Kadesh and Shur and repeats his earlier mistake, claiming that Sarah is his sister (Gen 20:1–2).

From there Abraham journeyed toward the territory of the Negeb and lived between Kadesh and Shur; and he sojourned in Gerar. 2 And Abraham said of Sarah his wife, “She is my sister.” And Abimelech king of Gerar sent and took Sarah. 

Gur, “To Sojourn.” The verb gur means “to live temporarily in a foreign land.”
The precarious nature of sojourning that characterized the account of Lot’s guests continues as Abraham sojourns among foreigners in Gerar.
Abraham’s sojourn in Gerar echoes an earlier trip to Egypt, where Pharaoh seized the beautiful Sarah only to have his house afflicted with plagues from God (Gen 12:10–20).

Gen 20:3–7
Taking Abraham at his word, Abimelech, the king of Gerar, takes Sarah into his harem, but before he touches her, God appears to him in a dream. God reveals to Abimelech that Sarah is Abraham’s wife and declares that he will die for taking her.

. 3 But God came to Abimelech in a dream by night and said to him, “Behold, you are a dead man because of the woman whom you have taken, for she is a man’s wife.” 4 Now Abimelech had not approached her. So he said, “Lord, will you kill an innocent people? 5 Did he not himself say to me, ‘She is my sister’ And she herself said, ‘He is my brother.’ In the integrity of my heart and the innocence of my hands I have done this.” 6 Then God said to him in the dream, “Yes, I know that you have done this in the integrity of your heart, and it was I who kept you from sinning against me. Therefore I did not let you touch her. 7 Now then, return the man’s wife, for he is a prophet, so that he will pray for you, and you shall live. But if you do not return her, know that you shall surely die, you and all who are yours.” 

How did the king respond? (4-5)
He defends his innocence
Because of general revelation, people recognize the sacred character of marriage (cf. Lev. 20:22; Deut. 22:22).
Tam Levav, “Integrity of Heart.”
The expression combines two common Hebrew words: tam, meaning “completeness,” and lebab (or leb), meaning “heart.” It refers to upright conduct or sincerity of action.
What did God say He had done to keep the king from sinning (6)
God did not let Abimelech have sexual relations with Sarah 
The primary significance of Gen 20 in the OT is its formal introduction of the role of a prophet
Abraham is the first “prophet” in the Bible (Gen 20:7). The Hebrew word used most often to refer to a prophet is navi’, which occurs more than 300 times in the OT.
Many connect the status to Abraham’s reception of divine revelation in the Sodom incident
This appearance also clearly identifies Abraham as a prophet who is given foreknowledge of God’s plans and judgments.
Others identify Abraham’s role as an intercessor as his qualification for the title “prophet”
Abraham’s compassion and sense of righteousness and justice prove him a worthy prophet. 
He pleads, like the weeping prophet Jeremiah, for the deliverance of the righteous in Sodom and Gomorrah.
Abraham intercedes as a prophet, not as one who has been wronged (unlike Num. 12 and Job 42). 
In his role as intercessor for the Gentiles, he prefigures Jesus Christ (Isa. 53:12; Rom. 8:34). 
We in the church are often sinful and failing, but still we are called to be the intercessors for those who do not receive Jesus Christ.
Contra Jonah

Gen 20:8-10
God promises to spare the king if he promises to return Sarah. The next day, Abimelech summons Abraham, asking why he has endangered Abimelech’s house by lying about his wife.

8 So Abimelech rose early in the morning and called all his servants and told them all these things. And the men were very much afraid. 9 Then Abimelech called Abraham and said to him, “What have you done to us? And how have I sinned against you, that you have brought on me and my kingdom a great sin? You have done to me things that ought not to be done.” 10 And Abimelech said to Abraham, “What did you see, that you did this thing?” 
Abimelech response reflects a widespread ancient Near Eastern value that adultery was “the great sin” (Hamilton 1995, 67). 
Legal documents from Ugarit, Egypt, and elsewhere in the ancient Near East indicate that adultery was an unacceptable practice (Sarna 1989, 143). 
Hittite law bears strong similarity to the situation in Gen 20; an adulterer who could prove his ignorance of a woman’s marital status at the time of the offense was acquitted of his crime (Mathews 2005, 252).

Gen 20:11–16
After Abraham explains his actions, Abimelech returns Sarah and gives Abraham a generous gift. 

11 Abraham said, “I did it because I thought, ‘There is no fear of God at all in this place, and they will kill me because of my wife.’ 12 Besides, she is indeed my sister, the daughter of my father though not the daughter of my mother, and she became my wife. 13 And when God caused me to wander from my father’s house, I said to her, ‘This is the kindness you must do me: at every place to which we come, say of me, “He is my brother.” ’ ”
14 Then Abimelech took sheep and oxen, and male servants and female servants, and gave them to Abraham, and returned Sarah his wife to him. 15 And Abimelech said, “Behold, my land is before you; dwell where it pleases you.” 16 To Sarah he said, “Behold, I have given your brother a thousand pieces of silver. It is a sign of your innocence in the eyes of all who are with you, and before everyone you are vindicated.” 

How did Abraham justify his conduct? What arrangement did Sarah and Abraham have that led to this deceit? (Question: How do you respond to repeated failures, weaknesses and sins?)
Abraham defends himself to Abimelech, saying that Sarah is his half sister, and he had asked her to identify herself as his sister whenever they traveled
To make matters worse, Abraham now incriminates both God and Sarah. The verb Abraham uses for wander (tāʿá) means to wander about hopelessly and aimlessly often in a hostile environment
Sarah is named as a consenting member in the trick.
Marriage to a half sister is prohibited by later Israelite law, but during the time of the patriarchs, it was culturally acceptable (compare Lev 18:9, 11; Deut 27:22)
Leviticus 18:9
You shall not uncover the nakedness of your sister, your father’s daughter or your mother’s daughter, whether brought up in the family or in another home.
Leviticus 18:11
You shall not uncover the nakedness of your father’s wife’s daughter, brought up in your father’s family, since she is your sister.
Deuteronomy 27:22
Cursed be anyone who lies with his sister, whether the daughter of his father or the daughter of his mother.’ And all the people shall say, ‘Amen.’
Abimelech gives gifts to Abraham (20:14–15) and to Sarah (20:16) to honor God and their special relationship with him, not to compensate for guilt (cf. 12:19–20). 
a thousand shekels. This is a fabulously large sum. A Babylonian laborer, usually paid a half shekel per month, would have had to work 167 years to earn such a sum.
God not only delivers his elect out of dreadful peril but blesses them with unexpected and undeserved riches

Gen 20:17-18
God has closed the wombs of the women of the king’s house, but when Abraham prays for Abimelech’s house, God blesses it with children ().

17 Then Abraham prayed to God, and God healed Abimelech, and also healed his wife and female slaves so that they bore children. 18 For the Lord had closed all the wombs of the house of Abimelech because of Sarah, Abraham’s wife. [1]


[1] The Holy Bible: English Standard Version. (2001). (Ge 20:1–18). Wheaton: Standard Bible Society.

If God can answer Abraham’s prayer for sterile pagan women, how much more for Abraham’s wife?

Theological reflections 
God’s sovereign grace is clearly revealed in this chapter. 
On the brink of Isaac’s conception (see 18:10–14; 21:1–2), Abraham places the program of redemption in jeopardy. 
God extends justice to Abimelech but mercy to Abraham and Sarah. 
Salvation depends on the faithful Lord, not on his unfaithful servants.
Application 
reflect on the sins and bad decisions I have made and remember that my salvation does not depend on those things
Remember that I stand in grace and must learn to think in grace
There is a general “moral standard” to which all people adhere. (“Behold, you are a dead man because of the woman whom you have taken, for she is a man’s wife.” 20:3)
Genesis begins with the formation of every person in the image of God. 
According to Paul, God has given everyone a general revelation of himself (Rom. 1:19–20)
It is on this basis that God judges and interacts with humanity.
Abraham provides a model for the Christian in the modern pluralistic world. In that world, God holds each person accountable for a fundamental fear of God and essential consideration of human relationships.. 
Although Abraham is in the wrong, Abimelech must ask Abraham, God’s elect instrument of salvation, to intercede for him. 
God’s human covenant partner, who nearly brought death to Abimelech by his scheming (20:3), is still the means by which God gives life and blessing (20:17–18).
We in the church are often sinful and failing, but still we are called to be the intercessors for those who do not receive Jesus
We might have hoped that by this time in Abraham’s life, he would be able to trust God with Sarah. Instead, Abraham’s fear and doubt lead him to a familiar sin. 
Like Abraham, we face the frustration of our weaknesses and sins. 
The Apostle Paul expresses this shared frustration in Rom 7:14–25: “I do not understand my own actions. For I do not do what I want, but I do the very thing I hate” (Rom 7:15 nrsv). 
But Paul’s reflections do not end with this despair. He reminds us that, by the power of the indwelling Holy Spirit, we are able to overcome sin: “Wretched man that I am! Who will rescue me from this body of death? Thanks be to God through Jesus Christ our Lord” (Rom 7:24–25a).

1. To where did Abraham move next?

To Gerar, in the territory of the Negeb between Kadesh and Shur

2. Who was king in that area?

Abimelech

3. What deceit did Abraham do, and where else in Genesis do we find that he did a similar thing?

He told King Abimelech that Sarah was his sister. He did the same thing in Egypt in Genesis 13.

4. What did God say to the king about it and how did the king respond?

God told the king he was as good as dead for taking Sarah. The king responded with fearful innocence.

5. What did God say He had done to keep the king from sinning, and what did He tell the king to do about the situation?

God did not let Abimelech have sexual relations with Sarah and told him to return her to Abraham

6. What did the king say to Abraham about it?

The king asked Abraham why did he do such a thing to him? Why did he lie and put his kingdom in danger’s way?

7. How did Abraham justify his conduct? (Think: As the situation unfolded, who appears to have the greater fear of God, Abraham or Abimelech?)

Abraham justified his conduct with the half-truth, that Sarah was his half sister through his father

8. What arrangement did Sarah and Abraham have that led to this deceit? (Think: How old was Sarah at this time and what does that tell you about her?)

That wherever they sojourned Sarah would say that Abraham is only her brother.

9. What did Abimelech do to compensate Abraham and Sarah?

Abimelech gave Abraham sheep, oxen, servants, and silver.

10. What did Abraham do for Abimelech and his people, and why was this needed?

Abraham prayed to God for Abimelech which was needed because God had caused all the women to be barren in the king’s household. 
