        <Document ID="350">
            <Title>The Ongoing Struggle with Sin</Title>
            <Text>“From there Abraham journeyed toward the territory of the Negeb and lived between Kadesh and Shur; and he sojourned in Gerar. And Abraham said of Sarah his wife, ‘She is my sister.’ And Abimelech king of Gerar sent and took Sarah” (Genesis 20:1-2). After the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah, for some reason Abraham journeyed to Gerar. Once there, he repeats the earlier sin he committed in Egypt, claiming that Sarah is his sister. As we discovered in the account of the angel’s visit with Lot, traveling in foreign lands proved to be quite dangerous. Instead of trusting God’s protection, Abraham resorts to deception in order to protect himself at the expense of Sarah. Even after having dined with the Lord and having witnessed the awesome display of God’s power in the destruction of Sodom, Abraham resorted to self-reliance in order to escape danger. 
Abraham’s experience reflects our own: we often repeat the same old sins and mistakes. Like Abraham, in our faith journey moments of great displays of faith are often intermingled with moments of disobedience. Oftentimes, the moments of disobedience are occasioned by a lack of prayerful diligence. On the eve of his crucifixion, Jesus warned his disciples to “watch and pray that you may not enter into temptation” (Matthew 26:40). He issued this warning because despite our best intentions, challenging circumstances will arise to test our resolve.  Like Peter who displayed overconfidence in self but still denied the Lord, we will resort to our old, sinful responses when depending on our own resources to deal with trials and temptations. 
