            <Title>The Ongoing Need for God's Grace</Title>
            <Text>Abraham repeated the same old sin and endangered the purpose of God by risking Sarah’s life, but God gracefully intervened to straighten out the mess. Abimelech, the king of Gerar had taken Sarah but before he had sexual contact with her, God appeared to him in a dream. God warned Abimelech that he was a good as dead for taking Sarah (Genesis 20:3). The king responded by defending his innocence - he had been deceived by Abraham’s brother-sister narrative. Abimlech’s response reveals that people outside of the covenant have God’s moral law stamped on their conscience. For one, he acknowledged the sanctity of marriage. Two, Abimelech acknowledged God’s sovereignty over nations and three, he appealed to God’s justice and righteousness (Genesis 20:4-5). The Lord struck fear in Abimelech’s heart and commanded him to return Sarah. In turn, Abraham, who is a prophet, would pray for Abimelech and his people.
In this passage, Abimelech’s character shines more brightly than does Abaraham’s. However, God does not abandon Abraham despite his grave mistake. He intervenes to save Sarah, to preserve the seed promise, to save Abimelech, and to restore Abraham. What a wonderful picture of grace and mercy! Just as God powerfully intervened to deliver the covenant couple from their, He has given us the power to overcome those old sinful habits that seek to pull us down. Our power is found in the indwelling Holy Spirit, given to us by God as a guarantee of protection and victory over sin. We will always struggle against the desires of the old man. However, as we prayerfully commune with God, renew our minds with and obey Scripture, and seek encouragement from the fellowship of the saints, the Spirit will give us the inner strength to resist sin.</Text>
        </Document>
        <Document ID="352">
            <Title>The Ongoing Need for Repentance</Title>
            <Text>The experience of God’s grace and mercy must be met with repentance. God used Abimelech’s fear of the Lord to highlight Abraham’s need for repentance. After hearing from the Lord, Abimelech summoned Abraham, asking why did he endanger Abimelech’s kingdom by lying about Sarah. Hamilton notes that Abimelech’s response reflects a widespread ancient Near East value that adultery was “the great sin” (Hamilton, p. 67). His response also shows that Abraham’s sin had a wider range of impact than he may have thought. Such is the nature of sin. Abraham attempted to justify his conduct with the premise that Abimelech and his people did not fear the Lord (Genesis 20:11). Next, he attempted to cover up his deception by revealing that Sarah was truly his half-sister. Finally, he shifts responsibility by saying it was God who caused him to wander in hostile environments and thereby, Sarah consented from the beginning of their journeys to use the brother-sister trick to escape from danger! Thus we learn that through years of journeying and fellowship with, Abraham never relinquished the deceitful brother-sister narrative. 
Again, Abraham’s experience is often our own. We allow the fear of man and circumstances to drive us to act in ways contrary to God’s will. At times, selfishness may drive our behaviors. We hold on to sinful habits deemed somewhat non-trivial, such as impatience, pride, gossip, judgmental attitudes, etc. God will providentially arrange circumstances through which we will become aware of the seriousness of sins which we deem ‘respectable’. Just as God used Abimelech to rebuke Abraham, He will use people in our lives to correct and make us aware of the gravity of our sins. Our daily prayers should include petitions for the Lord to search our hearts and try our thoughts in order to reveal any grievous sins in our lives and to lead us in the everlasting way (Psalms 139:23-24)!
Through God’s mercy, Abimelech returned Sarah to Abraham with generous gifts. In return, Abraham prayed to God to heal Abimelech’s wife and female slaves who had become sterile through the ordeal (Genesis 20:17-18). This act of compassionate intercession reveals Abraham’s penitent heart. Along with the sense of justice and righteous he displayed when interceding for Sodom, it also shows him to be a worthy prophet. Like Abraham, we in the church cannot claim sinless perfection, but we are called to promote justice in the world and to intercede for the lost around us. 

