 (nāsâ). vb. test, try, tempt, put one to the test. Describes God putting people to the test or people testing God.

The verb nāsâ can be used to describe the act of God testing individuals and groups, such as Abraham (Gen 22:1), Israel (in both the wilderness and the promised land; e.g., Exod 15:25; 16:4; Deut 8:2; Judg 3:4), the tribe of Levi (Deut 33:8), Hezekiah (2 Chr 32:31), and a psalmist (Psa 26:2). 

God’s testing has particular purposes: 
to prevent people from sinning (Exod 20:20b); 
to see whether they will follow God’s instructions (Exod 16:4); 
to discover the motives of the heart and to keep his commandments (Deut 8:2; 2 Chr 32:31); 
to do good in the end to those he tests (Deut 8:16); 
and to see whether they love him wholeheartedly (Deut 13:4) and whether they will obey the his way (Judg 2:22; 3:4). 

The verb nāsâ also refers on several occasions to Israel putting God to the test during the wilderness journey (e.g., Exod 17:7; Num 14:22; Deut 6:16; Psa 78:18; 95:9). It is used once to describe the occasion of Ahaz testing God (Isa 7:12).

 The verb nāsâ can also be used in the sense of testing the feasibility of some actions or matters (Deut 4:34; 28:56; Judg 6:39; 1 Sam 17:39; Eccl 7:23). Kim, S. H. (2014). Testing. D. Mangum, D. R. Brown, R. Klippenstein, &amp; R. Hurst (Eds.), Lexham Theological Wordbook. Bellingham, WA: Lexham Press.
